## 1. Water Supply Concept

- Provide preliminary water planning for kitchen, bathrooms, laundry/storage, technical room, terrace/outdoor kitchen placeholder, and exterior taps.
- Keep mains water and tank supply options open until site utilities, water quality, winter access, and local authority requirements are verified.
- Route water services through accessible, insulated, maintainable zones; avoid external walls, unheated voids, and inaccessible terrace build-ups wherever possible.
- Final pipe sizing, pressure balancing, backflow prevention, shutoff strategy, and disinfection/commissioning are excluded.

## 2. Mains Water Option

- Mains connection is assumed possible only as a placeholder.
- Connection point, meter chamber, authority fees, pressure, flow, backflow requirements, easements, and winter protection are TBD.
- The design must include isolation, drain-down, pressure regulation where needed, and accessible maintenance points after professional review.

## 3. Water Tank Option

- Optional storage tank: {{ off_grid.water_tank_l }} L.
- Tank use may support intermittent supply, off-grid operation, firefighting reserve discussions, or temporary resilience, but no final capacity is certified.
- Tank location, structural support, burial/freezing risk, overflow, venting, filtration, water quality, cleaning access, and pump intake protection require professional design.

## 4. Pump and Pressure Concept

- A booster pump/pressure set may be required for tank supply or low mains pressure.
- Pump selection, duty/standby strategy, pressure vessel sizing, noise/vibration isolation, dry-run protection, filtration, bypasses, and controls are TBD.
- Technical room maintenance access must be preserved for pumps, filters, valves, tanks, electrical isolation, and leak detection.

## 5. Cold Water Distribution

- Cold water should serve all configured wet rooms and any approved exterior water points.
- Include accessible isolation valves for each wet room or branch, appliance isolation, backflow protection where required, and labelled service routes.
- Pipe routes must be protected from frost, puncture, condensation, and inaccessible concealment.

## 6. Hot Water Distribution

- Hot water is expected at kitchen sink, washbasins, showers, utility sinks, and other configured fixtures that require hot water.
- Recirculation, point-of-use heaters, pipe insulation, scald protection, balancing, and energy losses are TBD.
- Long hot-water runs should be minimized and coordinated with bathroom/kitchen stacking and technical room location.

## 7. Domestic Hot Water Source

- Domestic hot water is assumed to coordinate with the air-to-water heat pump concept and technical room equipment.
- Cylinder size, legionella control, backup heater, mixing valve, expansion vessel, pressure relief discharge, and service clearances are TBD.
- Final DHW design requires mechanical/plumbing review and manufacturer data.

## 8. Kitchen Plumbing

- Kitchen fixtures from YAML are included in the fixture schedule.
- Expected needs include sink supply/waste, dishwasher connection, shutoff valves, leak protection, trap access, and coordination with cabinetry.
- Final drain route, venting, appliance details, and penetrations through structure are TBD.

## 9. Bathroom Plumbing

- Bathrooms require coordinated supply, waste, trap, vent, waterproofing, floor falls, fixture support, service access, and mechanical extract.
- Shower areas require particular review of waterproofing interfaces, drain capacity, trap access, and slope to drain.
- This package does not approve bathroom layouts, wet-room waterproofing, or sanitary code compliance.

## 10. Laundry/Utility Plumbing

- Laundry/storage and technical room fixtures are included in the fixture schedule.
- Washing machine connections, utility sink, floor drain, overflow risk, vibration, leak detection, and maintenance access require detailed design.
- Utility areas should keep valves, filters, drains, pumps, and equipment reachable after finishes are installed.

## 11. Exterior Taps

- Exterior taps are placeholders for terrace/outdoor use and require freeze-safe detailing.
- Include internal isolation valves, drain-down, backflow protection, frost-resistant fittings where appropriate, and slope to drain.
- Exterior water points must be coordinated with terrace waterproofing and electrical safety zones.

## 12. Freeze Protection

- Frost depth placeholder: {{ site.frost_depth_placeholder_cm }} cm.
- Mountain conditions and vacancy periods create elevated freeze risk for exterior taps, tank/pump lines, terrace plumbing, foundation penetrations, and unheated service voids.
- Freeze protection may require burial depth, insulation, heat tracing, drain-down, frost-free valves, heated technical spaces, monitoring, and emergency access.

## 13. Wastewater Concept

- Wastewater planning covers sanitary discharge from bathrooms, kitchen, laundry/storage, technical room drains, and approved exterior wet points.
- Final pipe slopes, diameters, venting, cleanouts, inspection chambers, grease handling, backflow/flood protection, and treatment connection are TBD.
- No local wastewater approval is implied by this generated document.

## 14. Septic Tank Option

- Septic system option is subject to local approval, soil conditions, groundwater level, setbacks, access for emptying, and environmental constraints.
- Percolation/infiltration assumptions must come from site investigation and authority requirements.
- This package does not size a septic tank, approve a leach field, or replace environmental permitting.

## 15. Biological Treatment Plant Option

- Biological treatment plant option is subject to local approval, power reliability, maintenance contracts, discharge route, sampling/access needs, and manufacturer requirements.
- Backup power, alarm handling, winter operation, and service vehicle access require review.
- This package does not select or approve a treatment plant.

## 16. Vent Pipe Concept

- Sanitary ventilation is required in concept, but vent pipe sizing and routing are not final.
- Vent routes must coordinate with roof penetrations, snow, wind, odor control, condensation, air admittance rules where allowed, and maintenance access.
- Final vent strategy must be designed by licensed professionals and reviewed against local requirements.

## 17. Rainwater Drainage

- Rainwater drainage must respond to roof area, standing seam metal roof conditions, snow melt, ice, site slope, discharge routes, and erosion control.
- Gutters, downpipes, snow guards, heated sections, splash blocks, soakaways, channels, and outfalls are placeholders until drainage calculations are performed.
- Site slope placeholder: {{ site.slope_percent }}%; drainage must avoid directing runoff toward foundations, neighbors, access roads, or unstable slopes.

## 18. Terrace Drainage

- Terrace area: {{ terrace.terrace_area_m2 }} m2.
- Terrace drainage must coordinate surface falls, waterproofing build-up, scuppers/drains, overflow paths, guard posts, door thresholds, snow/ice, and maintenance access.
